<exercise xml:id="exam3-f25-q3">
<statement>
The function
<m>
    \displaystyle f(x) = \frac{3-4e^{-x}}{2+2e^{-x}}
</m>
has two horizontal asymptotes. Use limits to carefully determine the equations of each asymptote. Unsupported work will not receive credit.
</statement>
<answer>
    <p>
        <m>y=\frac{3}{2}</m> is a horizontal asymptote since <md> \lim_{x \rightarrow \infty} f(x) = \lim_{x \rightarrow \infty} \frac{3-4e^{-x}}{2+2e^{-x}} = \frac{3}{2}. </md>
    </p>
    <p>
        <m>y=-2</m> is another horizontal asymptote since, using L'Hopital's rule, we have <md> <mrow> \lim_{x \rightarrow -\infty} f(x) \mathstrut \amp = \lim_{x \rightarrow -\infty} \frac{3-4e^{-x}}{2+2e^{-x}} </mrow>
            <mrow> \amp = \lim_{x \rightarrow -\infty} \frac{4e^{-x}}{-2e^{-x}} </mrow>
            <mrow> \amp = -2. </mrow>
        </md>
    </p>
</answer>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="exam3-f25-q4">
<statement>
A function satisfying
<m>
  f(0)=-1
</m>
that is differentiable everywhere has the graph of
<m>
  f'(x)
</m>
as shown in <xref ref="F25Ex3q4"/>. 
<figure xml:id="F25Ex3q4">
  <caption><m>f(x)</m> is differentiable everywhere.</caption> 
  <image xml:id="Exam3F25q4pic" width="50%" >
<description>
</description>
    <latex-image>
 \begin{tikzpicture}[thick,scale=0.8]
\draw[step=1cm,color=black,dotted] (-3,-5) grid (3,3);
   \draw [black!80,line width=0.3pt,-latex] (0,0) -- (3,0) node [below] at (2.5,0) {$x$};
   \draw [black!80,line width=0.3pt,-latex] (0,0) -- (-3,0);
   \draw [black!80,line width=0.3pt,-latex] (0,0) -- (0,3) node [right] at (0,2.5) {$y$};
   \draw [black!80,line width=0.3pt,-latex] (0,0) -- (0,-5);
%%\draw[color=linecolor, line width=1pt,domain=0.5:4.25]   plot (\x,{4/(\x+1))}) node [above] at (1.65,2) {$\displaystyle f(x)$};
\draw[color=linecolor, line width=2pt,smooth,domain=-2.75:2.75]   plot (\x,{-0.5*(\x-1.5)*(\x-1.5)*(\x+2.5)}) node [above] at (-2,1) {$\displaystyle f'(x)$};
\fill [black] (1.5,0) circle(3pt) node [above] at (1.5,0.05) {$(1.5,0)$}; 
\fill [black] (-1.16,-4.750) circle(3pt) node [below] at (-1.16,-4.8) {$\left(-\frac{7}{6}, -4.75\right)$}; 
\fill [black] (-2.5,0) circle(3pt) node [above] at (-2.25,0.05) {$(-2.5,0)$}; 
\fill [black] (0,-2.8125) circle(3pt) node [right] at (0,-2.8) {$(0,-2.75)$}; 
\foreach \x/\xtext in {  -2/-2, -1/-1, 1/1, 2/2}
    \draw[shift={(\x,0)}] (0pt,3pt) -- (0pt,-3pt) node[below] {$\xtext$};
\foreach \y/\ytext in {-4/-4, -3/-3, -2/-2, -1/-1, 1/1, 2/2}
    \draw[shift={(0,\y)}] (-2pt,0pt) -- (2pt,0pt) node[left] {$\ytext$};
\end{tikzpicture}
    </latex-image>
  </image>
</figure>
<ol marker="(a)">
  <li>
    <p>
      Construct a first-derivative sign chart to determine interval(s) of the domain where
      <m>
        f
      </m>
      is increasing and where
      <m>
        f
      </m>
      is decreasing.
    </p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>
      Construct a second-derivative sign chart to determine interval(s) of the domain where
      <m>
        f
      </m>
      is concave up and where
      <m>
        f
      </m>
      is concave down. Identify all inflection points as well.  
    </p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>
      Assume that all of the interesting information about
      <m>
        f'(x)
      </m>
      is shown in <xref ref="F25Ex3q4"/>. Does
      <m>
        f(x)
      </m>
      have any local minima? If so, where? If not, why not? Does it have any local maxima?
    </p>
  </li>
  </ol>
  </statement>
  <answer>
<ol marker="(a)">
  <li>
    <p>
      <m>f(x)</m> is increasing on <m>(-\infty, -2.5)</m> and decreasing on <m>(-2.5,-1.5) \cup (-1.5,\infty)</m>.  
    </p>
    <figure xml:id="F25Ex3q4A">
  <caption>A first derivative sign chart.</caption> 
  <image xml:id="Exam3F25q4Apic" width="90%" >
<description>A firat derivative sign chart.
</description>
    <latex-image>
\begin{tikzpicture}[thick,scale=1] [domain=-3:3]
   \draw [black!80,line width=0.5pt,-latex] (0,0) -- (4,0) node [below] at (3.5,0) {$f'(x)$};
   \draw [black!80,line width=0.5pt,-latex] (0,0) -- (-6,0);
   \draw [red] node [above] at (-4,0.25) {$+$};
   \draw [red] node [above] at (-1.5,0.25) {$-$};
   \draw [red] node [above] at (2,0.25) {$-$};
   \draw [black!80,line width=0.5pt] (-3,0.25) -- (-3,-0.25) node [below] at (-3,-0.25) {$-2.5$};
   \draw [black!80,line width=0.5pt] (0,0.25) -- (0,-0.25) node [below] at (0,-0.25) {$1.5$};
\end{tikzpicture}
    </latex-image>
  </image>
</figure>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>
      <m>f(x)</m> is concave down on <m>(-\infty, -\frac{7}{6}) \cup (1.5,\infty)</m> and concave up on <m>(-\frac{7}{6},1.5)</m>.  There are inflection points at <m>x=-\frac{7}{6}</m> and <m>x=1.5</m>.
    </p>
    <figure xml:id="F25Ex3q4B">
  <caption>A second derivative sign chart.</caption> 
  <image xml:id="Exam3F25q4Bpic" width="90%" >
<description>A second derivative sign chart.
</description>
    <latex-image>
\begin{tikzpicture}[thick,scale=1] [domain=-3:3]
   \draw [black!80,line width=0.5pt,-latex] (0,0) -- (4,0) node [below] at (3.5,0) {$f''(x)$};
   \draw [black!80,line width=0.5pt,-latex] (0,0) -- (-6,0);
   \draw [red] node [above] at (-4,0.25) {$-$};
   \draw [red] node [above] at (-1.5,0.25) {$+$};
   \draw [red] node [above] at (2,0.25) {$-$};
   \draw [black!80,line width=0.5pt] (-3,0.25) -- (-3,-0.25) node [below] at (-3,-0.25) {$-\frac{7}{6}$};
   \draw [black!80,line width=0.5pt] (0,0.25) -- (0,-0.25) node [below] at (0,-0.25) {$1.5$};
\end{tikzpicture}
    </latex-image>
  </image>
</figure>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>
      <m>f(x)</m> has a local maximum at <m>x=-2.5</m> via the second derivative test.  <m>f(x)</m> has no local minimum since <m>f(x)</m> does not change from decreasing to increasing anywhere.
    </p>
  </li>
</ol>
  </answer>
  </exercise>

<exercise xml:id="exam3-f25-q5">
<statement>
 The velocity of a falling object at time
 <m>
     t
 </m>
 seconds is given by
 <m>
     v(t) = 9-3t
 </m>
 feet per second. Determine the
 <alert>
     distance
 </alert>
 the object has traveled during the time interval of
 <m>
     t=0
 </m>
 to
 <m>
     t=2
 </m>
 seconds. Illustrate this value with a well-labeled diagram.
  </statement>
  <answer>
    <p>
      The distance traveled is <m>6+\frac{1}{2}(2)(6) = 12</m> feet.  
    </p>
    <figure xml:id="F25Ex3q5ans">
  <caption>The velocity of a falling object gives the distance it has traveled via area under the curve.</caption> 
  <image xml:id="Exam3F25q5anspic" width="50%" >
<description>
</description>
    <latex-image>
\begin{tikzpicture}[thick,scale=1] [domain=-3:3]
  \fill [red!50] (0,0) -- (2,0) -- (2,1) -- (0,3) -- (0,0);
   \draw [black!80,line width=0.5pt,-latex] (-1,0) -- (4,0) node [below] at (3.5,0) {$t$};
   \draw [black!80,line width=0.5pt,-latex] (0,-1) -- (0,4) node [right] at (0,3.5) {$v(t)$};
   \draw [linecolor] node [below] at (2,0) {$2$};
   \draw [linecolor] node [below] at (3,0) {$3$};
   \draw [linecolor] node [left] at (0,3) {$9$};
   \draw [linecolor] node [left] at (0,1) {$3$};
   \draw [linecolor,line width=0.5pt] (-1,4) -- (4,-1);
\end{tikzpicture}
    </latex-image>
  </image>
</figure>
  </answer>
  </exercise>

<exercise xml:id="exam3-f25-q6">
<statement>
<ol marker="(a)">
  <li>
    <p>
       Compute the value of <m>
           \displaystyle \sum_{k=1}^{5}2k+3.
       </m>
    </p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>
      Express the sum
      <m>
          \displaystyle 3+7+11+\cdots+39
      </m>
      using sigma notation.
    </p>
  </li>
</ol>
</statement>
  <answer>
<ol marker="(a)">
  <li>
    <p>
      <m>5+7+9+11+13=45</m>
    </p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>
      <m>\displaystyle \sum_{k=0}^9 (3+4k) </m>
    </p>
  </li>
  </ol>
  </answer>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="exam3-f25-q7">
<statement>
A rancher wants to create a rectangular plot of 20,000 square feet bounded on one long east-west side by a river. Due to strong southern winds, fencing costs 4 times as much per foot for the east-west side as for the north-south sides. What dimensions minimize the fencing cost?
  </statement>
  <answer>

  <p>
    Let <m>x</m> denote the width of the rectangular plot perpendicular to the river,
    and let <m>y</m> denote the length parallel to the river. Since fencing is
    required on only three sides, the total cost is
  </p>

  <md>
    C = 4y + 2x.
  </md>

  <p>
    The area constraint is
  </p>

  <md>
    xy = 20,000.
  </md>

<figure xml:id="F25Ex3q7ans"> 
<caption>A rectangular plot bordering a river.</caption>
  <image xml:id="Exam3F25q7anspic" width="50%" >
<description>A plot near a river.
</description>
    <latex-image>
\begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.02]
\draw (0,0) rectangle (200,100);
\node at (100,50) {$20,\!000$};

\node[above] at (100,100) {$x$};
\node[below] at (100,0) {$x$};
\node[left] at (0,50) {$y$};

\draw[decorate,decoration={brace,amplitude=6pt}]
  (220,0) -- (220,100);
\node[right] at (220,50) {River};
\end{tikzpicture}
    </latex-image>
  </image>
  </figure>

  <p>
    Solving the area constraint for <m>y</m> gives
  </p>

  <md>
    y = \frac{20,000}{x}.
  </md>

  <p>
    Substitute this expression into the cost function:
  </p>

  <md>
    C(x)
      = 4\left(\frac{20,000}{x}\right)+2x
      = \frac{80,000}{x}+2x,
  </md>

  <p>
    where <m>x&gt;0</m>.
  </p>

  <p>
    Differentiate:
  </p>

  <md>
    C'(x)
      = -80,000x^{-2}+2.
  </md>

  <p>
    Set the derivative equal to zero and solve:
  </p>

  <md>
    -80,000x^{-2}+2=0,
  </md>

  <md>
    x^2=40,000,
  </md>

  <md>
    x=\pm 200.
  </md>

  <p>
    Since <m>x</m> represents a length, <m>x&gt;0</m>, so the only relevant
    critical value is
  </p>

  <md>
    x=200.
  </md>

  <p>
    A sign analysis shows that <m>C'(x)&lt;0</m> for <m>0&lt;x&lt;200</m>
    and <m>C'(x)&gt;0</m> for <m>x&gt;200</m>. Therefore,
    <m>C(x)</m> is minimized when <m>x=200</m>.
  </p>

  <p>
    Using the area constraint,
  </p>

  <md>
    y=\frac{20,000}{200}=100.
  </md>

  <p>
    Therefore, the dimensions that minimize the fencing cost are
  </p>

  <md>
    x=200\text{ feet},
    \qquad
    y=100\text{ feet}.
  </md>

  <p>
    The optimal plot is <m>200</m> feet by <m>100</m> feet.
  </p>
  </answer>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="exam3-f25-q8">
<statement>
The rectangles in <xref ref="F25Ex3q8"/> illustrate a left-endpoint Riemann sum
<m>
    \displaystyle \sum_{k=1}^{n} f(x_{k}^{*}) \ \Delta x
</m>
for the function
<m>
    \displaystyle f(x) = -\frac{x^{2}}{3}+ 3x
</m>
on the interval
<m>
    [4,8]
</m>
. 
<figure xml:id="F25Ex3q8" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
      <caption>A Riemann sum.</caption>
      <image source="images/LeftRiemannSumQuadratic.jpg" width="50%">
        <description></description>
      </image>
</figure>
<ol marker="(a)">
  <li>
    <p>
      What is the value of
      <m>
          \Delta x
      </m>
      in this Riemann sum? 
    </p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>
      Give an explicit formula for
      <m>
          x_{k}^{*}
      </m>
      in terms of the index
      <m>
          k
      </m>
      in the Riemann sum.  
    </p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>
      Illustrate a right-endpoint Riemann sum
      <m>
          R_{2}
      </m>
      using
      <m>
          n=2
      </m>
      rectangles for
      <m>
          f(x)
      </m>
      on the interval
      <m>
          [0,3]
      </m>
      on the graph. Then, calculate the value of
      <m>
          R_{2}
      </m>
      .
    </p>
  </li>
</ol>
  </statement>
  <answer>
<ol marker="(a)">
  <li>
    <p>
      <m>\Delta x = 0.5</m>
    </p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>
      <m>x_k^* = 4+(k-1)(0.5)</m> or <m>x_k^* = 3.5 + 0.5k</m>
    </p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>
      <md> <mrow> R_2 \mathstrut \amp = f(1.5)(1.5) + f(3)(1.5) </mrow>
        <mrow> \amp = \left[ -\frac{1.5^2}{3}+3(1.5) \right](1.5) + \left[ -\frac{3^2}{3} + 3(3)\right](1.5) </mrow>
        <mrow> \amp 14.625 </mrow>
      </md>
    </p>
  </li>
</ol>
  </answer>
  </exercise>

  <exercise xml:id="exam3-f25-q9">
<statement>
The graph of <m>f''(x)</m> is given in <xref ref="F25Ex3q9"/>.  
<figure xml:id="F25Ex3q9" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
      <caption>A graph of <m>f''(x)</m>.</caption>
      <image source="images/SecondDerTestFall2025.jpg" width="50%">
        <description>Graph of a smooth curve with a local minimum near x = -2, a local maximum near x = 1, and another local minimum near x = 2 where the curve touches the x-axis before rising sharply.</description>
      </image>
</figure>
<ol marker="(a)">
  <li>
    <p>
      If
      <m>
          x=-2
      </m>
      and
      <m>
          x=1
      </m>
      are critical numbers of
      <m>
          f(x)
      </m>
      , determine if each is a local minimum, local  maximum, neither, or if more information is needed.
    </p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>
      Identify the
      <m>
          x
      </m>
      -value(s) for which
      <m>
          f(x)
      </m>
      has an inflection point.
    </p>
  </li>
</ol>
</statement>
<answer>
<ol marker="(a)">
  <li>
    <p>
      <m>x=-2</m> gives a local maximum since <m>f''(-2) &lt; 0</m>.  <m>x=1</m> gives a local minimum since <m>f''(1) &gt; 0</m>.
    </p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>
      There are inflection points at <m>x=-3</m> and <m>x=0</m> since <m>f''(x)</m> changes sign.
    </p>
  </li>
</ol>
</answer>
</exercise>

</exercises>

</section>
</handout>